licy and global politics. The imperial power dynamics of ancient Athens and Rome provided fertile ground for the deliberations of many classical thinkers who wrote on the nature of empire: contemplating political sovereignty, autonomy, and citizenship as well as war, peace, and civilization in a world where political boundaries were strained and contested. The contributors to this collection prompt similar questions with their essays and promote a serious contemporary consideration of empire in light of the predominance of the United States and of the doctrine of liberal democracy.Featuring essays from some of the leading thinkers in the fields of political science, philosophy, history, and classics, Enduring Empire illustrates how lessons gleaned from the Athenian and Roman empires can help us to understand the imperial trajectory of global politics today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aImperialismxHistory. 0aImperialismxPhilosophy. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / Diplomacy.2bisacsh1 aBagby, Laurie M. Johnson, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBalot, Ryan K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBradshaw, Leah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEckstein, Arthur M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHendrickson, David C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeyking, John Von, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKellow, Geoffrey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKoivukoski, Toivo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKoivukoski, Toivo, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMattern, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4http